    <Drives>
      <Para>ADRMSInstall</Para>
    </Drives>
    <Synopsis>Provides cmdlets for installing, updating, or uninstalling the Active Directory Rights Management Services server role.</Synopsis>
    <DetailedDescription>
      <para>The Active Directory Rights Management Services (AD RMS) Deployment Windows PowerShell Provider implements a set of cmdlets and a drive namespace that let you install, update, and uninstall the AD RMS server role in Windows Server 2008 R2 by using Windows PowerShell commands and scripts. 

To begin installing an AD RMS server by using Windows PowerShell, you use the Import-Module cmdlet to import the ADRMS module. You then create a drive that represents the root of the deployment namespace for the AD RMS server. When you create the drive, you specify the type of cluster (root or licensing) for which the server is being provisioned if the server is the first server in the cluster; otherwise, you specify that the server is joining an existing cluster. Next, you traverse the containers in the drive namespace to set properties on items in those containers that represent options and settings required to install the AD RMS server role. For example, if you create a drive named serv1: for installing AD RMS as the first server in a root cluster, you would specify a non-default cluster Web site by navigating to the serv1:\ClusterWebSite container and then setting the webSiteName property of the container to the URL of the cluster Web site. In many cases, you can use “built-in” cmdlets, such as get-childitem, to navigate the namespace and to get and set properties of containers and items. You can use most file-system naming conventions, such as relative paths and wildcard characters, to work with the ADRMSInstall drive namespace. After setting the necessary installation options, you complete the installation by running the Install-ADRMS cmdlet. This cmdlet installs the AD RMS server role in addition to any dependencies, and then provisions the server according to the options specified by the properties you set in the ADRMSInstall drive namespace.

An ADRMSInstall drive namespace provides a hierarchy of containers that closely matches the settings presented by the Add Role Wizard when installing the AD RMS server role. The following list shows the names of the containers in the drive namespace:

\
\ADFSSupport 
\ClusterDatabase
\ClusterDatabase\DatabaseInstance
\ClusterDatabase\DAtabaseInstance\&lt;Instance_Name&gt;
\ClusterKey
\ClusterKey\CSP
\ClusterKey\CSP\&lt;CSP_Name&gt;
\ClusterWebsite

The ADRMSInstall provider also implements two cmdlets, Uninstall-ADRMS and Update-ADRMS, that you can use to uninstall the AD RMS server role or to upgrade the server role following an operating-system upgrade. These cmdlets do not require you to create a drive because they do not require you to specify any options before you run them.
</para>
    </DetailedDescription>
